{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":2999675,"name":"Dylan Watson","username":"Dylan_Watson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan_watson/{size}/11665_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:09:11.824Z","cooked":"<p>My apologies for making two of these threads, the first one was an accident.</p>
<p>For a number of years now, my team has written wrappers around robot component classes (SparkMAX, VictorSPX, etc.) in order to use some of our own logic (all written in C++). When working with the updated REVLib and <code>CANSparkMax</code>, we wanted an interface in order to easily get the position of the encoder. For reference, we only use SparkMAX controllers for NEO motors, so it is always a <code>kHallSensor</code> encoder.</p>
<p>In order to get the encoder, it seems that we have to call the <code>GetEncoder()</code> method, which returns a <code>SparkMaxRelativeEncoder</code> object (not pointer). Our first attempt was to call this method whenever we needed to retrieve an encoder position, however we quickly realized that this throws the error <code>GetEncoder() has already been called for SPARK MAX</code>.</p>
<p>After this, we tried holding the <code>SparkMaxRelativeEncoder</code> as a member variable of our wrapper class. However, <code>SparkMaxRelativeEncoder</code> doesn’t have a default constructor, which is necessary to hold an object as a member variable in a class as far as I know.</p>
<p>Does anyone have any tips on this? I hope I am just missing something simple within REVLib and overthinking this. Thanks!</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:23:09.714Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":131,"reads":77,"readers_count":76,"score":670.4,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Dylan Watson","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":2,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":25685,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/1","custom_user_title":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null,"can_vote":false},{"id":2999683,"name":"Cédric","username":"GodCed","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/858c86/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:17:29.043Z","cooked":"<p>(I’ll assume C++ because you mention pointers)</p>
<p>Does <a href="https://github.com/REVrobotics/SPARK-MAX-Examples/blob/master/C%2B%2B/Read%20Encoder%20Values/src/main/cpp/Robot.cpp" rel="noopener nofollow ugc">this example</a>  work for you?</p>
<p>I don’t see your full code but you should be able to call GetEncoder() to initialize your member, thus avoiding repeated calls and bypassing the default constructor problem.</p>","post_number":2,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:17:29.043Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":73,"readers_count":72,"score":24.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Cédric","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"link_counts":[{"url":"https://github.com/REVrobotics/SPARK-MAX-Examples/blob/master/C%2B%2B/Read%20Encoder%20Values/src/main/cpp/Robot.cpp","internal":false,"reflection":false,"clicks":30}],"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":45989,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/2","custom_user_title":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2999684,"name":"Dylan Watson","username":"Dylan_Watson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan_watson/{size}/11665_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:22:43.047Z","cooked":"<p>We map all of our components, and the CAN ID’s associated with them, to an XML file that is read on code startup. Because of this, the CANSparkMax itself is not initialized right in the wrapper class definition, but instead in the constructor of our wrapper class (I hope that makes sense). This leads us to having  <code>rev::SparkMaxRelativeEncoder enc;</code> in our wrapper class’ member variables, and <code>enc = motor.getEncoder()</code> in the wrapper class’ constructor, which presents the default constructor issue.</p>","post_number":3,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:22:43.047Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":2,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":3,"reads":69,"readers_count":68,"score":33.8,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Dylan Watson","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":45989,"username":"GodCed","name":"Cédric","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/858c86/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":25685,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/3","custom_user_title":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2999693,"name":"Cédric","username":"GodCed","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/858c86/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:40:44.249Z","cooked":"<p>Gotcha. Then you’ll have to store a pointer to your encoder, but make your own pointer! That should work, as the copy constructor for the encoder class is defined but it’s untested.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">// wrapper.hpp
class Wrapper
{
  // Encoder smart pointer
  std::unique_ptr&lt;rev::SparkMaxRelativeEncoder&gt; m_encoder;

  // Drive
  rev::CanSparkMax m_drive;
};

// wrapper.cpp
Wrapper::Wrapper()
{
  // Construct your drive
  m_drive = ...;

  // Get the drive's encoder and store a copy into your pointer
  m_encoder = std::make_unique&lt;rev::SparkMaxRelativeEncoder&gt;(m_drive.GetEncoder());
}

double Wrapper::GetEncoder()
{
  return m_encoder-&gt;GetWhatever();
}
</code></pre>","post_number":4,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:43:13.585Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":3,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":6,"reads":53,"readers_count":52,"score":45.6,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Cédric","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":25685,"username":"Dylan_Watson","name":"Dylan Watson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan_watson/{size}/11665_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":45989,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/4","custom_user_title":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2999696,"name":"Dylan Watson","username":"Dylan_Watson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan_watson/{size}/11665_2.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:47:58.952Z","cooked":"<p>Oh! I had thought about this, but tried it without <code>unique_ptr</code>, I just did it with <code>rev::SparkMaxRelativeEncoder * enc;</code> and <code>enc=&amp;(Max-&gt;GetEncoder());</code></p>
<p>I will give this a shot at the robotics shop later today. Thank you!!</p>","post_number":5,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:47:58.952Z","reply_count":1,"reply_to_post_number":4,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":4,"reads":41,"readers_count":40,"score":48.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Dylan Watson","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":"","reply_to_user":{"id":45989,"username":"GodCed","name":"Cédric","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/858c86/{size}.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[{"id":2,"count":1}],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":25685,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/5","custom_user_title":"3481 Mentor | CHS Volunteer","reactions":[{"id":"heart","type":"emoji","count":1}],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":1,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":2999700,"name":"Cédric","username":"GodCed","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/g/858c86/{size}.png","created_at":"2022-01-28T20:55:31.246Z","cooked":"<p>No problem. FYI, what you did with old style pointers should have worked like this:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">rev::SparkMaxRelativeEncoder* enc = new SparkMaxRelativeEncoder(Max-&gt;GetEncoder());
</code></pre>
<p>The trick is that you must create <strong>your own copy</strong> of the encoder object, else your pointer will point to garbage when the original object (returned by GetEncoder()) goes out of scope at the end of the constructor.</p>
<p>But really old style should not be used anymore because they put the burden of memory management on you and a good programmer is a lazy one.</p>","post_number":6,"post_type":1,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2022-01-28T20:55:31.246Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":5,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":1,"reads":40,"readers_count":39,"score":13.0,"yours":false,"topic_id":401638,"topic_slug":"issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder","display_username":"Cédric","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"reply_to_user":{"id":25685,"username":"Dylan_Watson","name":"Dylan Watson","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/dylan_watson/{size}/11665_2.png"},"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":45989,"hidden":false,"trust_level":2,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper"},"post_url":"/t/issues-with-rev-sparkmaxrelativeencoder/401638/6","custom_user_title":"Programming Mentor / CSA / FTAA / Scorekeeper","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3135543,"name":"system","username":"system","avatar_template":"/uploads/default/original/4X/9/3/2/93234578e69f55873c63fc00fe2d0d85f23bce55.png","created_at":"2023-01-28T20:56:18.779Z","cooked":"<p>This topic was automatically closed 365 days after the last reply. New replies are no longer allowed.</p>","post_number":7,"post_type":3,"posts_count":7,"updated_at":"2023-01-28T20:56:18.779Z","reply_count"